    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-cpb-vr-001",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "CFD hemolysis prediction vs. experimental RH index",
      "description": "Simulation predictions of the relative hemolysis index (RH) were compared against experimental measurements across five flow-speed operating points. Agreement was within 12% for four of five conditions. The fifth operating point — corresponding to the lowest flow rate (2.5 L/min, 3000 RPM) — exhibited a discrepancy of 28%, attributed to transitional flow phenomena not fully captured by the steady-state k-ω SST turbulence model at low Reynolds numbers. This edge case is not fully covered by the current validation dataset, and the model's predictive fidelity under these specific low-flow conditions remains a known limitation of the present assessment. The overall validation is considered adequate for the stated COU; the risk associated with this limitation is acceptable."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-cpb-vr-002",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Mesh independence and solver convergence study",
      "description": "Three mesh densities (coarse: 1.2M, medium: 4.8M, fine: 11.1M elements) were evaluated. The Richardson extrapolation-based Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for the medium mesh was 2.3%, satisfying the required threshold of less than 5% for MRL 2. Residuals converged to below 1e-5 for all flow variables."
    }
  ],
